    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense for a lecture. I'm just a bit worried about how to handle the pushback in class. Some students might ask if the 'substantive' side is basically just judges making up their own moral standards and imposing them on the country. How can I explain that the substantive due process view isn't just a subjective preference, but actually a more rigorous way to uphold the Constitution compared to the procedural view?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process is a way to ensure that the government doesn't just follow the rules, but also respects our fundamental rights. It's not about judges imposing their own moral views; it's about protecting the rights that are already guaranteed by the Constitution. The procedural due process is important, but it's like having a rulebook that doesn't protect us from being unfairly treated. Substantive due process is like having a referee in a game who makes sure the rules aren't just followed, but that they're fair and don't hurt anyone. It's a way to keep the government in check and make sure our rights are actually protected, not just in theory but in practice. So, while some people might see it as judges making up their own rules, it's really about making sure the Constitution is what really counts, not just the letter of the law. It's a way to make sure our rights are really, really protected.",
      "source": "target",
